5.3.1 Public keys
-----------------

Public keys are globally unique identifiers for hyperdrives.  They make
up the first part of a ‘hyper://’ URL.  Public keys are
52-character-long z-base-32
(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Base32#z-base-32) encoded keys generated
from your master key (see *note Master key::) and a *note seed: Seeds.
string.  When you run ‘hyperdrive-new’ and type a new seed, the gateway
automatically generates a new public key.


File: hyperdrive.info,  Node: Nicknames,  Next: Petnames,  Prev: Public keys,  Up: Naming

5.3.2 Nicknames
---------------

Nicknames are public, memorable names which you can give to your own
hyperdrives to make them easier for others to recognize.  Other users
can see your nicknames but cannot change them.

   Nicknames are stored in each hyperdrive inside
‘/.well-known/host-meta.json’ under the ‘name’ key, as specified in
RFC6415 (https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc6415#section-6.1).


File: hyperdrive.info,  Node: Petnames,  Next: Seeds,  Prev: Nicknames,  Up: Naming

5.3.3 Petnames
--------------

Petnames are locally unique hyperdrive identifiers.  You can give a
petname to any hyperdrive you load, whether you created it or not.


File: hyperdrive.info,  Node: Seeds,  Next: DNS domains,  Prev: Petnames,  Up: Naming

5.3.4 Seeds
-----------

Seeds are used in tandem with your secret master key (see *note Master
key::) to generate public keys (see *note Public keys::).  The same seed
and master key will always produce the same public key, so a
hyperdrive’s seed cannot be changed.  Seeds are local but not secret.
To share a drive, you must use a public key or DNS domain (see *note DNS
domains::).


